//Two Sum II - Input Array Is Sorted
//Given a 1-indexed array of integers numbers that is already sorted in non-decreasing order,
//find two numbers such that they add up to a specific target number.
//Return the indices of the two numbers (1-indexed).
//You must use only constant extra space.
//Example 1:
//Input: numbers = [2,7,11,15], target = 9
//Output: [1,2]
//Example 2:
//Input: numbers = [2,3,4], target = 6
//Output: [1,3]
//Example 3:
//Input: numbers = [-1,0], target = -1
//Output: [1,2]


Brute Force Approach ->

Check every possible pair of indices and see whether their sum equals the target.

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& numbers, int target) {

        for(int i = 0; i < numbers.size(); i++) {
            for(int j = i + 1; j < numbers.size(); j++) {
                if(numbers[i] + numbers[j] == target) {
                    return {i + 1, j + 1};
                }
            }
        }
        return {};
    }
};

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n²)
where:
n = size of numbers
Reason:
For every element, we may check all remaining elements.

Space Complexity -> O(1)
Reason:
No extra data structures are used.

Optimal Approach -> (Two Pointers)

class Solution {
public:                 
    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& numbers, int target) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = numbers.size() - 1;
        while(left < right) {
            int sum = numbers[left] + numbers[right];
            if(sum == target) {
                return {left + 1, right + 1};
            }
            else if(sum < target) {
                left++;
            }
            else {
                right--;
            }
        }
        return {};
    }
};

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = size of numbers
Reason:
Each pointer moves at most n times.

Space Complexity -> O(1)
Reason:
Only two pointers are used.

Corner Cases

1. Two Elements Only
numbers = [-1,0]
target = -1
Output:
[1,2]

2. Negative Numbers
numbers = [-5,-3,2,8]
target = -8
Output:
[1,2]

3. Answer at Extremes
numbers = [1,2,3,4,9]
target = 10
Output:
[1,5]

4. Answer in the Middle
numbers = [1,2,4,6,10]
target = 8
Output:
[2,4]

5. Duplicate Values
numbers = [1,3,3,4]
target = 6
Output:
[2,3]

